Upgrading existing Confluence data to a clustered environment as per this [documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/DOC/Confluence+Cluster+Installation+with+Existing+Data] no longer works, as the following Cluster properties are not added to confluence.cfg.xml after the cluster installation:
{code}
<property name="confluence.cluster">true</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.address">233.143.107.205</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.interface">eth4</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.name">test</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.ttl">1</property>
{code}

h3.Workaround
# Use the [list-interfaces.jar|https://jira.atlassian.com/secure/attachment/24536/list-interfaces.jar] found in this feature request to identify the network interface for the cluster: https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONF-10979 . Use it in this property in confluence.cfg.xml:
{code}
<property name="confluence.cluster.interface">eth4</property>
{code}
# Navigate to http://path-to-confluence/admin/cluster/hashclustername.jsp , enter the desired *cluster name*, and hit *Generate*. Use the resulting cluster address with your cluster name in the following properties in confluence.cfg.xml :
{code}
<property name="confluence.cluster.name">test</property>
 <property name="confluence.cluster.address">233.143.107.205</property>
{code}
# Add the following properties along with the properties added earlier to confluence.cfg.xml:
{code}
<property name="confluence.cluster">true</property>
 <property name="confluence.cluster.ttl">1</property>
{code}
In the end, you should get something like this:
{code}
<property name="confluence.cluster">true</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.address">233.143.107.205</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.interface">eth4</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.name">test</property>
    <property name="confluence.cluster.ttl">1</property>
{code}

